doctor_vignette: A 54-year-old female presents with persistent joint pain and swelling, primarily in her hands and wrists. On examination, there is significant tenderness, bilateral swelling, and morning stiffness lasting over an hour. Laboratory tests reveal elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, along with an increased ESR. X-rays show joint erosions in the metacarpophalangeal joints.

A 67-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a chronic cough producing sputum for the past few months. Physical examination reveals prolonged expiratory phase, wheezing, and decreased breath sounds bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry indicates a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio consistent with obstructive airway disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with chronic diarrhea and abdominal bloating that has persisted for several months. On physical examination, she has notable weight loss and signs of malnutrition, including dry skin and hair loss. Serological tests reveal elevated tissue transglutaminase antibodies (tTG-IgA) and positive IgA endomysial antibodies, suggesting an autoimmune process. A subsequent duodenal biopsy confirms the presence of villous atrophy.

A 58-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe chest pain radiating to his left arm, accompanied by shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is diaphoretic and has a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg with an elevated heart rate of 110 bpm. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of tremors in his right hand that have progressively worsened over the past year. Physical examination reveals a resting tremor, bradykinesia, and rigidity in the upper limbs. There is a shuffling gait noted during ambulation, and he demonstrates difficulty initiating movement. MRI of the brain shows no acute changes, supporting the clinical diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.

A 10-year-old male presents with recurrent episodes of spontaneous bleeding from the gums and prolonged bleeding after minor cuts. Physical examination reveals easy bruising and joint swelling in the knees. Laboratory tests show aPTT of 60 seconds (normal 30-40 seconds) and normal PT, indicating a deficiency in factor VIII.

A 10-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of wheezing and shortness of breath, especially during play and at night. Physical examination reveals diffuse wheezing on auscultation and decreased breath sounds. Peak expiratory flow rate measurement shows a reduction of 60% from her personal best, indicating obstructive airflow limitation.

A 35-year-old female presents with unintentional weight loss, increased anxiety, and palpitations over the past month. On examination, she has a rapid heart rate of 110 beats per minute, fine tremors in her hands, and an enlarged thyroid gland. Laboratory tests reveal elevated levels of free T4 and suppressed TSH, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and fatigue for the past three months. Physical examination reveals a butterfly rash across her cheeks and photosensitivity. Laboratory tests show elevated anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels, consistent with autoimmune activity.
actual_diagnosis: Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and mild lower extremity edema. On physical examination, she has elevated blood pressure and decreased urine output. Laboratory results reveal a serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 30 mL/min, indicating significant renal impairment.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 10-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and difficulty breathing. Physical exam reveals digital clubbing and wheezing on auscultation. A sweat test demonstrates an elevated chloride level of 80 mmol/L, confirming the suspicion of cystic fibrosis.

A 55-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which started suddenly during the night. On examination, the toe is erythematous, warm, and tender to touch, with limited range of motion. Serum uric acid levels are markedly elevated at 9.2 mg/dL, and joint aspiration reveals needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals under polarized light.

A 22-year-old female presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and episodes of sudden muscle weakness triggered by laughter. Physical examination reveals normal neurological function except for mild cataplexy. Polysomnography shows decreased REM latency and multiple sleep onset REM periods. The MSLT confirms a mean sleep latency of 4 minutes with two sleep-onset REM episodes.

A 65-year-old male with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease presents with a chief complaint of worsening cough and fever for three days. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion in the right lower lung field. A chest X-ray shows a right lower lobe consolidation, and sputum culture identifies Klebsiella pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Klebsiella pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J15.0

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with progressive chorea and difficulty with coordination over the past year. Neurological examination reveals abnormal movements of her limbs and facial grimacing, along with mild cognitive decline. Genetic testing reveals the presence of the CAG repeat expansion in the HTT gene, confirming the diagnosis.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent abdominal pain and bloating, often relieved by defecation. Physical examination reveals mild tenderness in the lower abdomen without guarding or rebound tenderness. Laboratory tests, including complete blood count and metabolic panel, are unremarkable, and no imaging studies are indicated. The symptoms have been occurring for over six months with no identifiable organic cause.
actual_diagnosis: Irritable bowel syndrome, ICD-10 code K58.9

doctor_vignette: A 5-year-old boy presents with recurrent fractures after minimal trauma. On physical examination, he has blue sclera and a noticeable bowing of his lower limbs. X-rays reveal multiple healed and healing fractures in various stages, along with osteopenic changes. Genetic testing confirms a mutation in the COL1A1 gene, consistent with osteogenesis imperfecta.

A 25-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and recurrent infections over the past month. On physical examination, she exhibits pallor and petechiae on her extremities. Complete blood count reveals a hemoglobin level of 8 g/dL, a platelet count of 30,000/mm³, and a white blood cell count of 2,000/mm³, indicating severe cytopenias.

A 10-year-old male of Mediterranean descent presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, he has noticeable splenomegaly and conjunctival pallor. A complete blood count reveals microcytic anemia with a hemoglobin level of 8 g/dL and elevated levels of fetal hemoglobin (HbF).

A 34-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent headaches occurring more than 15 days per month for the past six months. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the pericranial muscles and no neurological deficits. A brain MRI shows no acute abnormalities, ruling out secondary causes of headache.

A 52-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and swelling in her hands and wrists for the past three months. Physical examination reveals bilateral tenderness and swelling of the metacarpophalangeal joints, with morning stiffness lasting over an hour. Laboratory tests show elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, along with an elevated ESR.

A 65-year-old male presents with fatigue, bruising, and recurrent infections over the past month. Physical examination reveals pallor and multiple ecchymoses on the extremities. Complete blood count shows anemia (Hb 8.5 g/dL), thrombocytopenia (platelets 45,000/μL), and leukocytosis with 25% blasts. Bone marrow biopsy confirms the presence of myeloblasts consistent with acute myeloid leukemia.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myeloid leukemia, ICD-10 code C92.0

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of red, scaly patches on her elbows and knees that have been persistent for several months. On physical exam, there are well-defined, erythematous plaques covered with silvery-white scales. No laboratory tests are necessary for diagnosis; however, a skin biopsy may confirm the presence of hyperkeratosis and neutrophilic infiltration. The patient has a family history of psoriasis, further supporting the diagnosis.

A 32-year-old African American female presents with persistent cough and shortness of breath for the past three months. Physical examination reveals bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and erythema nodosum on her lower extremities. A chest X-ray shows enlarged lymph nodes and a CT scan confirms the presence of granulomas in the lungs. Laboratory tests show elevated serum angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) levels, supporting the diagnosis.

A 75-year-old male presents to the emergency department with complaints of increasing shortness of breath and swelling in his legs over the past month. On examination, he has elevated jugular venous pressure, bilateral pitting edema, and crackles in the lung fields. A chest X-ray reveals cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, and a BNP level is markedly elevated at 800 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 12-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of excessive thirst and frequent urination over the past month. On physical examination, he is noted to have a thin build and dry mucous membranes. Laboratory results show a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and a HbA1c of 9.5%.
actual_diagnosis: Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance. Physical examination reveals dry skin, bradycardia, and a swollen face. Laboratory tests show elevated TSH levels and low free T4 levels, confirming the diagnosis.

A 68-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent low back pain after a minor fall. Physical examination reveals a decreased height of 3 cm since her last visit and tenderness over the lumbar spine. A DEXA scan shows a T-score of -2.8 at the lumbar spine and -2.5 at the hip, indicating significant bone density loss.

A 45-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain radiating to his back, accompanied by nausea and vomiting. On physical examination, he exhibits tenderness in the epigastric region and mild jaundice. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum lipase and amylase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid suggesting pancreatitis.

A 72-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that began earlier in the day. On examination, his heart rate is irregularly irregular at 130 beats per minute, and he has mild edema in his lower extremities. An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response, and his electrolytes show a potassium level of 3.2 mEq/L.

A 24-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations, reporting that he hears voices telling him to harm himself. On physical examination, he shows signs of disorganized thinking and has difficulty maintaining coherent speech. Routine lab tests, including complete blood count and metabolic panel, are unremarkable, and a CT scan of the head reveals no structural abnormalities.

A 72-year-old female presents with fatigue and weakness for the past few months. On physical examination, she has pale conjunctiva and a heart rate of 92 bpm. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 10.2 g/dL, low serum iron, and normal ferritin levels, suggestive of anemia of chronic disease. A history of rheumatoid arthritis is noted, contributing to her condition.
actual_diagnosis: Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.8

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with fatigue and mild edema in the lower extremities. Physical examination reveals elevated blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg and bilateral ankle swelling. Laboratory tests show a serum creatinine level of 2.2 mg/dL and an estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating moderate kidney impairment.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease stage 3, ICD-10 code N18.3

doctor_vignette: A 10-year-old African American male presents with severe abdominal pain and fatigue after experiencing a recent upper respiratory infection. On examination, he has pallor and tenderness in the right upper quadrant. A complete blood count shows a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL, and peripheral blood smear reveals sickle-shaped red blood cells. The patient also has elevated bilirubin levels, indicating hemolysis.
actual_diagnosis: Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old female presents with widespread musculoskeletal pain lasting over six months, accompanied by fatigue and sleep disturbances. On physical exam, tenderness is noted in multiple tender points, particularly in the neck, shoulders, and lower back. Routine lab tests including CBC and metabolic panel show no significant abnormalities, and imaging studies are unremarkable.

A 24-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent fatigue and night sweats for the past month. Physical examination reveals cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. A chest X-ray shows mediastinal lymphadenopathy, and a lymph node biopsy confirms the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells.

A 54-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past several months. On physical examination, he is overweight with a BMI of 32 and has reduced sensation in his feet. Laboratory tests reveal a fasting blood glucose level of 160 mg/dL and an HbA1c of 7.5%.
actual_diagnosis: Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 22-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of severe headache and high fever for the past 24 hours. On physical examination, he exhibits neck stiffness and photophobia. A lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with a white blood cell count of 1,200 cells/mm³, predominantly neutrophils, and positive Gram stain for Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 25-year-old female presents to the emergency department with her first seizure episode, characterized by a generalized tonic-clonic seizure lasting approximately two minutes. On physical examination, she is alert but disoriented postictally, with no focal neurological deficits noted. A CT scan of the head shows no acute intracranial abnormalities, and routine blood tests reveal normal electrolytes and glucose levels.

A 55-year-old male presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of severe chest pain radiating to the back. On examination, he has a blood pressure differential of 30 mmHg between the arms and a diastolic murmur. Chest X-ray shows a widened mediastinum, and a CT angiogram confirms an aortic dissection extending from the ascending aorta.

A 28-year-old female presents with fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. Physical examination reveals pale conjunctiva and a heart rate of 110 bpm. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 9.5 g/dL, low serum ferritin at 10 ng/mL, and elevated total iron-binding capacity (TIBC).
actual_diagnosis: Anemia due to iron deficiency, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A  seventeen-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent facial acne for the past six months. Physical examination reveals multiple open and closed comedones, papules, and pustules primarily on the forehead and cheeks, with some scarring noted. No laboratory tests or imaging studies are required for diagnosis, as the condition is clinically evident.

A 35-year-old female presents with a 6-month history of persistent nasal congestion and facial pressure. Physical examination reveals tenderness over the maxillary sinuses and postnasal drip. A CT scan of the sinuses shows mucosal thickening and obstruction of the ostiomeatal complex. Allergy testing indicates sensitivity to dust mites.

A 55-year-old male presents to the clinic with complaints of frequent headaches and dizziness. On physical examination, his blood pressure is recorded at 160/100 mmHg, and he exhibits mild bilateral retinal changes. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated serum creatinine level of 1.5 mg/dL, indicating possible kidney involvement due to hypertension.

A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of cough and shortness of breath for the past three days. Upon examination, she exhibits decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right lower lung field. A chest X-ray reveals a right lower lobe infiltrate consistent with pneumonia. Blood tests show elevated white blood cell count and CRP levels, indicating infection.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia, unspecified organism, ICD-10 code J18.9

doctor_vignette: A 67-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a chronic cough producing sputum for the past year. Physical examination reveals wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and use of accessory muscles during respiration. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and pulmonary function tests indicate an FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.58, consistent with obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain, especially after prolonged walking or standing. On physical examination, there is notable crepitus and tenderness along the medial joint line of the right knee, with a reduced range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation, consistent with osteoarthritis.
actual_diagnosis: Osteoarthritis of the knee, ICD-10 code M17.9

doctor_vignette: A 32-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on his elbows and knees that have persisted for several months. On physical examination, erythematous plaques with silvery scales are noted on extensor surfaces, and there is evidence of nail pitting. No significant lab tests are required for diagnosis, but a skin biopsy reveals hyperkeratosis and acanthosis, consistent with psoriasis.

A 45-year-old female presents with progressive unilateral hearing loss in the right ear over the past six months, accompanied by occasional tinnitus. On physical examination, there is a diminished response to auditory stimuli on the right side. MRI of the brain reveals a 2.5 cm mass at the cerebellopontine angle consistent with an acoustic neuroma.

A 58-year-old female presents with severe, sharp facial pain along the right side of her face, described as electric shocks triggered by light touch. Physical examination reveals tenderness over the right trigeminal nerve distribution with no neurological deficits. MRI of the brain shows a neurovascular conflict at the root entry zone of the right trigeminal nerve.

A 4-year-old male presents with a 5-day history of high fever, conjunctival injection, and a rash on his torso. On examination, he has cracked lips, strawberry tongue, and cervical lymphadenopathy. Laboratory tests reveal elevated inflammatory markers, including a significantly elevated ESR and CRP, along with thrombocytosis.

A 24-year-old female presents with joint hypermobility and recurrent joint dislocations, particularly in the shoulders and knees. Physical examination reveals skin that is velvety and hyper-elastic, along with bruising easily. Genetic testing confirms the presence of pathogenic variants in the COL5A1 gene, consistent with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.

An 8-year-old male presents with progressive muscle weakness and difficulty climbing stairs. Physical examination reveals waddling gait, calf hypertrophy, and positive Gowers' sign. Serum creatine kinase levels are markedly elevated at 12,000 U/L, and genetic testing confirms the presence of mutations in the dystrophin gene.
actual_diagnosis: Duchenne muscular dystrophy, ICD-10 code G71.0

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old male from rural South America presents with persistent fatigue and mild chest pain. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and a heart rate of 110 bpm. An ECG shows signs of right bundle branch block, and serologic tests are positive for Trypanosoma cruzi antibodies, confirming the diagnosis.

A 5-year-old male presents with developmental delay and seizures. On physical examination, he has facial angiofibromas and a hypopigmented macule on his left arm. MRI of the brain reveals multiple cortical tubers and subependymal nodules, consistent with the diagnosis.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of extreme mood swings over the past six months, including episodes of elevated energy and decreased need for sleep followed by periods of severe depression. Physical examination reveals a labile affect, with inappropriate laughter during the interview and a flat mood during depressive phases. No critical lab or imaging results are necessary for this diagnosis, as the evaluation is primarily clinical based on symptomatology.

A 67-year-old male presents with progressive dyspnea and a persistent dry cough over the past six months. On physical examination, fine crackles are auscultated at the bases of the lungs, and there is clubbing of the fingers. High-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) of the chest reveals reticular patterns and honeycombing consistent with interstitial lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, ICD-10 code J84.112

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old male presents with complaints of enlarged hands and feet over the past several years, along with facial changes including a protruding jaw and enlarged nose. Physical examination reveals coarse facial features, increased spacing between teeth, and a glove size increase from large to extra-large. Serum insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels are markedly elevated, and an MRI of the pituitary gland shows a 2 cm adenoma.

A 15-year-old male presents with progressive fatigue, tremors, and personality changes over the past few months. Physical examination reveals Kayser-Fleischer rings in the cornea and a liver enlargement. Serum ceruloplasmin is significantly low at 10 mg/dL, and 24-hour urinary copper excretion is elevated at 500 mcg.

A 28-year-old female presents with double vision and persistent muscle weakness, especially in her arms and legs that worsens with activity. On physical examination, she demonstrates ptosis and increased fatigue after prolonged eye closure. Repetitive nerve stimulation shows a decremental response, and acetylcholine receptor antibodies are positive.

A 22-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of severe right lower quadrant abdominal pain that began 12 hours ago. On physical examination, he has tenderness at McBurney's point and rebound tenderness is noted. A CT scan of the abdomen reveals an enlarged, non-complex appendix with surrounding inflammatory changes.

A 28-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of blurred vision and right-sided weakness. Neurological examination reveals decreased sensation in the right arm and a positive Babinski sign on the right side. MRI of the brain shows multiple periventricular white matter lesions consistent with demyelination.

A 30-year-old female presents with muscle cramps and tingling in her fingers. On physical exam, she exhibits Chvostek's sign and Trousseau's sign. Laboratory tests reveal low serum calcium levels (6.5 mg/dL) and elevated phosphate levels (5.5 mg/dL).

A 65-year-old female presents to the emergency department with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain that worsens with deep breathing. On examination, she is tachypneic with decreased breath sounds on the right side and exhibits unilateral leg swelling. A CT pulmonary angiogram reveals a large pulmonary embolism in the right main pulmonary artery.

A 65-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased appetite over the past few months. On physical examination, he has bilateral lower extremity edema and a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory tests reveal a serum creatinine level of 2.1 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating chronic kidney impairment.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

A 68-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent lower back pain that worsens with standing. A DEXA scan reveals a T-score of -2.8 in the lumbar spine, indicating osteoporosis.

A 72-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath. Physical examination reveals an irregularly irregular pulse and elevated blood pressure of 160/95 mmHg. An EKG shows rapid atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 120 bpm. Laboratory tests indicate elevated levels of B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) at 500 pg/mL, suggesting heart strain.

A 28-year-old woman presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and fatigue for the past three months. On physical examination, she has a malar rash, oral ulcers, and swelling in her wrists and knees. Laboratory tests reveal positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels, supporting the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: 9. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

On physical examination, he exhibits prolonged expiratory phase and bilateral wheezing. A peak flow measurement reveals 60% of his personal best, indicating significant obstruction. No recent infections or other respiratory illnesses were noted, and chest X-ray shows hyperinflation consistent with asthma.

A 54-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past few months. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, blood pressure of 140/85 mmHg, and diminished sensation in the feet. Laboratory results show a fasting blood glucose level of 180 mg/dL and an HbA1c of 8.2%.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

An 8-year-old male presents with fatigue and pallor over the past month. Physical examination reveals significant splenomegaly and petechiae on the skin. Complete blood count shows leukocytosis with a high percentage of blast cells, along with low hemoglobin and platelets.
actual_diagnosis: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia, ICD-10 code C91.0

doctor_vignette: A 25-year-old female presents to the emergency department after ingesting a peanut butter cookie, complaining of difficulty breathing and swelling of the lips. A rapid response team notes significant bronchospasm on auscultation, and her oxygen saturation is at 85%.

A lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with an elevated white blood cell count, predominantly neutrophils, and a positive Gram stain for Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 58-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, and blood pressure is 145/90 mmHg. Laboratory tests show a fasting blood glucose level of 180 mg/dL and HbA1c of 8.5%.

Laboratory tests reveal a serum protein electrophoresis showing monoclonal spike (M-protein) and elevated serum creatinine levels. A skeletal survey demonstrates lytic bone lesions in the vertebrae.

A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation after meals for the past three months. On physical examination, he is overweight with tenderness in the epigastric region but no rebound tenderness. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reveals moderate esophagitis, consistent with acid reflux disease.
actual_diagnosis: Acid reflux disease, ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old male presents with worsening asthma and new-onset purpura on his lower extremities. Physical examination reveals wheezing, nasal polyps, and tender subcutaneous nodules. Laboratory tests show eosinophilia and elevated ANCA (anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies) levels. A chest CT scan reveals bilateral pulmonary infiltrates.

A 72-year-old male presents with progressive memory loss and visual hallucinations, stating he frequently sees animals in his home. Physical examination reveals a shuffling gait and mild rigidity in the arms. Neuroimaging shows diffuse cortical atrophy with prominent changes in the occipital lobe. Cognitive testing indicates impaired executive function and attention.
actual_diagnosis: Dementia with Lewy bodies, ICD-10 code G31.83

doctor_vignette: A 24-year-old female with a history of type 1 diabetes presents with abdominal pain, nausea, and excessive thirst. On exam, she is tachycardic, has dry mucous membranes, and her breath has a fruity odor. Lab results reveal a blood glucose level of 450 mg/dL, arterial blood gas shows metabolic acidosis with a pH of 7.2, and urine analysis is positive for ketones.

A 10-year-old male presents with difficulties in social interactions and a strong focus on collecting train schedules. Physical examination reveals normal growth parameters and no neurological deficits, but he avoids eye contact and struggles with understanding social cues. There are no significant lab or imaging findings, but a detailed developmental history indicates delayed social milestones.

A 62-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of swelling and pain in her right leg that developed over the past three days. On physical examination, there is notable unilateral edema in the right calf, with tenderness upon palpation and a positive Homan's sign. A Doppler ultrasound reveals a thrombus in the right popliteal vein, confirming the suspicion of deep vein thrombosis.
actual_diagnosis: Deep vein thrombosis, ICD-10 code I82.90

doctor_vignette: A 34-year-old male presents with progressive weakness in both legs over the past week, accompanied by tingling sensations and difficulty walking. On examination, he shows reduced deep tendon reflexes and ascending muscle weakness. Nerve conduction studies reveal significantly reduced motor nerve conduction velocities, and lumbar puncture indicates elevated protein levels with normal white cell counts in the cerebrospinal fluid.

A 62-year-old male presents with acute left lower abdominal pain and fever. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the left lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and mild guarding. A CT scan of the abdomen shows inflamed diverticula in the sigmoid colon without abscess formation. Laboratory tests reveal leukocytosis with a white blood cell count of 14,000 cells/mm³.

A 28-year-old female presents with severe pelvic pain and dysmenorrhea that has worsened over the past year. On physical examination, there is tenderness in the posterior fornix and adnexal tenderness bilaterally. Transvaginal ultrasound reveals cystic lesions on the ovaries consistent with endometriomas. A pelvic MRI confirms the presence of endometrial tissue outside the uterus.

A 16-year-old female presents with complaints of inflamed, painful pimples on her face and back that have worsened over the past six months. On physical examination, multiple comedones, papules, and pustules are noted on the forehead, cheeks, and upper back. There are no significant lab or imaging results required for diagnosis as this condition is typically diagnosed clinically.

A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent dry cough and progressive shortness of breath over the past six months. On physical examination, bibasilar crackles are noted upon auscultation, and the patient demonstrates clubbing of the fingers. A chest CT scan reveals ground-glass opacities and reticular patterns consistent with interstitial lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Interstitial lung disease, ICD-10 code J84.9

doctor_vignette: A 75-year-old female presents with progressive memory loss and difficulty performing daily tasks over the past year. On physical exam, she exhibits disorientation to time and place, and her Mini-Mental State Examination score is 22/30. MRI of the brain shows bilateral hippocampal atrophy, consistent with Alzheimer's disease.
actual_diagnosis: Dementia due to Alzheimer's disease, ICD-10 code G30.9

doctor_vignette: A 68-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of high fever and confusion for the past 24 hours. On examination, she is tachycardic, hypotensive, and exhibits altered mental status. Laboratory results show elevated white blood cell count (18,000 cells/mm³) and a positive blood culture for E. coli.

A 27-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of abnormal vaginal discharge that has a fishy odor, particularly after intercourse. On physical examination, there is a thin, grayish discharge observed with a pH of 5.5 and a positive whiff test. Microscopic examination of the discharge reveals a significant presence of clue cells and a decrease in lactobacilli.

A 55-year-old male presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and loud snoring reported by his partner. On physical examination, he has a body mass index (BMI) of 32, enlarged tonsils, and a crowded oropharynx. A sleep study reveals multiple episodes of apnea and hypopnea, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Obstructive sleep apnea, ICD-10 code G47.33

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old male from rural South America presents with fatigue, fever, and swollen lymph nodes. Physical examination reveals conjunctivitis and a notable cardiomegaly on chest X-ray. Serology testing shows positive results for Trypanosoma cruzi antibodies.

A 12-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of excessive thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical exam reveals signs of dehydration, including dry mucous membranes and decreased skin turgor. Critical lab results show a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and the presence of ketones in the urine.
actual_diagnosis: Diabetes mellitus type 1, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 27-year-old female presents with fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. On physical examination, she has pale conjunctiva and tachycardia. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 9.5 g/dL, a mean corpuscular volume of 70 fL, and low serum ferritin levels.
actual_diagnosis: Iron deficiency anemia, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 62-year-old male presents with chest pain and shortness of breath on exertion. Physical examination reveals elevated blood pressure of 160/100 mmHg and bilateral pitting edema in the lower extremities. An echocardiogram shows left ventricular hypertrophy and reduced ejection fraction. Laboratory tests indicate elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels.
actual_diagnosis: Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 7-year-old male presents with developmental delays and learning difficulties. On physical examination, he exhibits a long face, large ears, and hyperflexible joints. Genetic testing reveals a CGG repeat expansion in the FMR1 gene, consistent with Fragile X syndrome.
actual_diagnosis: Fragile X syndrome, ICD-10 code F84.81

doctor_vignette: A 4-year-old male presents with a 5-day history of fever, irritability, and a rash. On physical examination, he has conjunctival injection, strawberry tongue, and cervical lymphadenopathy. Laboratory tests reveal elevated inflammatory markers, including an increased C-reactive protein (CRP) and erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR).

A 28-year-old male presents with chronic low back pain and stiffness that improves with activity but worsens during rest. Physical examination reveals limited lumbar flexion and tenderness over the sacroiliac joints. X-rays show bilateral sacroiliitis, and HLA-B27 testing is positive.

A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent fatigue and joint pain, particularly in her wrists and knees. On examination, she has palpable purpura on her lower extremities and mild edema. Laboratory tests reveal elevated ESR and CRP levels, alongside a positive ANCA test. Imaging studies show no evidence of vascular occlusion but suggest inflammation in the surrounding tissues.

A 45-year-old woman presents with progressive shortness of breath on exertion and fatigue over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a loud P2 heart sound and peripheral edema. Echocardiography shows an estimated right ventricular systolic pressure of 45 mmHg, indicating elevated pulmonary artery pressure. A chest CT scan shows no significant pulmonary embolism, but mild enlargement of the right ventricle is noted.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent severe headaches lasting 4 to 72 hours. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the pericranial muscles and normal neurological findings. No abnormalities are found in routine lab tests or brain imaging, which shows no acute changes.
actual_diagnosis: Migraine without aura, ICD-10 code G43.009

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with complaints of persistent skin tightening and difficulty swallowing. On physical exam, she exhibits thickened skin on her fingers and face, along with Raynaud's phenomenon. Laboratory tests reveal elevated anti-Scl-70 antibodies and pulmonary function tests indicate mild restrictive lung disease.

A 26-year-old female presents with recurrent painful nodules and abscesses in the axillary and groin areas over the past year. Physical examination reveals multiple draining sinuses, scarring, and inflammatory lesions in these regions. No laboratory abnormalities are noted, and imaging studies show subcutaneous inflammation without abscess formation.

A 45-year-old female presents with a palpable, painless nodule on the right side of her neck that has gradually increased in size over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a firm, non-tender mass in the right thyroid lobe, with no cervical lymphadenopathy noted. Ultrasound shows a solid, hypoechoic lesion measuring 2.5 cm with irregular margins, and fine needle aspiration cytology indicates suspicious for malignancy.

A 24-year-old male presents with infertility and decreased libido. On physical examination, he is noted to have tall stature, gynecomastia, and reduced muscle mass. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum estradiol levels and low testosterone levels, while karyotyping shows 47,XXY chromosomes.

A 45-year-old female presents with worsening muscle weakness, particularly in her eyelids and limbs, over the past month. On physical examination, she exhibits ptosis and significant fatigability with repetitive testing of the upper extremities. Serological testing reveals elevated acetylcholine receptor antibodies, supporting the diagnosis.

A 65-year-old male presents with fatigue, recurrent fevers, and easy bruising over the past month. Physical examination reveals pallor, petechiae on the lower extremities, and splenomegaly. Complete blood count shows a white blood cell count of 45,000/µL with 60% myeloblasts, hemoglobin of 8 g/dL, and platelet count of 30,000/µL.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myeloid leukemia, ICD-10 code C92.00

doctor_vignette: A 12-year-old male presents with excessive thirst, frequent urination, and unintentional weight loss over the past month. On physical examination, he is noted to have dry mucous membranes and a fruity odor on his breath. Critical lab results show a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and an HbA1c of 10.5%.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with fatigue, joint pain, and a butterfly-shaped rash across her cheeks. On examination, there is tenderness and swelling in multiple joints, particularly the wrists and knees. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and low complement levels, consistent with an autoimmune process.
actual_diagnosis: 7. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 67-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of worsening knee pain, particularly after prolonged standing and walking. On physical examination, there is noticeable crepitus, joint tenderness, and a decreased range of motion in the right knee. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Osteoarthritis of the knee, ICD-10 code M17.9

doctor_vignette: A 54-year-old male presents with complaints of persistent headaches and dizziness over the past month. On physical examination, his blood pressure is found to be 160/98 mmHg, with a notable finding of mild obesity. Routine laboratory tests show elevated serum creatinine levels at 1.4 mg/dL, suggesting possible kidney dysfunction related to hypertension.

A 75-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that began suddenly two hours ago. On examination, his heart rate is irregularly irregular at 120 beats per minute, and he has mild edema in his lower extremities. An electrocardiogram shows atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response. Basic labs reveal an elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) level, indicating heart failure.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath, worsening over the last six months. Physical examination reveals wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and a prolonged expiratory phase. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry indicates an FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.55, confirming airflow limitation.
actual_diagnosis: 8. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with chronic diarrhea and abdominal bloating for the past six months. Physical examination reveals mild abdominal distension and tenderness in the left lower quadrant. Laboratory tests show positive tissue transglutaminase (tTG) antibodies and a low hemoglobin level indicating anemia.

A 55-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which started suddenly last night. On physical examination, the affected joint is erythematous, warm, and tender to touch, with a limited range of motion. Serum uric acid levels are found to be elevated at 8.5 mg/dL, confirming the suspicion of gout.

A 72-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. Physical examination reveals bilateral lower extremity edema, an elevated jugular venous pressure, and crackles on lung auscultation. A chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, while laboratory tests reveal elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels.
actual_diagnosis: 10. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, scaly patches on her elbows and knees that have worsened over the past month. On physical examination, there are well-defined, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales on the extensor surfaces. No significant laboratory abnormalities were noted, and a skin biopsy confirms the presence of psoriatic changes.

A 45-year-old male presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, accompanied by nausea and vomiting. On physical examination, he exhibits tenderness in the upper abdomen and a slightly elevated heart rate. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum lipase and amylase levels, while an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid and an enlarged pancreas.

A 32-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and palpitations over the past month. Physical examination reveals a finely tremulous hand, moist skin, and a markedly enlarged thyroid gland (goiter). Laboratory tests show elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, indicating hyperthyroidism.

A 45-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of vertigo lasting 20-30 minutes, accompanied by tinnitus and a sensation of fullness in her left ear. On physical examination, she demonstrates nystagmus during the episodes and reports fluctuating hearing loss in the affected ear. An audiogram reveals low-frequency hearing loss consistent with endolymphatic hydrops, while MRI of the brain shows no other abnormalities.

A 68-year-old male presents with fatigue and weakness over the past month. Physical examination reveals pallor and mild splenomegaly. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 10 g/dL, elevated C-reactive protein, and low serum iron with normal ferritin levels, indicating anemia of chronic disease.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.8

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old female presents with widespread musculoskeletal pain lasting for more than three months, accompanied by fatigue and sleep disturbances. Physical examination reveals tenderness in multiple trigger points and a reduced range of motion in her shoulders and hips. Laboratory tests, including complete blood count and inflammatory markers, return normal, ruling out other conditions.

A 12-year-old African American male presents to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain and fatigue. Physical examination reveals pallor, jaundice, and splenomegaly. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL, elevated reticulocyte count, and peripheral blood smear reveals sickle-shaped red blood cells.
actual_diagnosis: 20. Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.1

doctor_vignette: A 67-year-old female presents with a complaint of persistent lower back pain that has worsened over the past month. Physical examination reveals a decrease in height and a kyphotic posture. A DEXA scan shows a T-score of -2.8 at the lumbar spine, indicating significant bone density loss. Laboratory tests reveal normal calcium and vitamin D levels.

A 25-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of intense itching and dry patches on her hands and elbows. On physical examination, there are erythematous, scaly lesions with crusting and lichenification noted in the affected areas. No specific lab tests are needed for diagnosis, but a skin scraping shows no evidence of fungal infection.

A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening left lower abdominal pain for two days, associated with fever and nausea. On physical examination, he has tenderness in the left lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and guarding. A CT scan of the abdomen reveals inflamed diverticula and pericolic fat stranding, consistent with diverticulitis.

A 14-year-old female presents to the emergency department with wheezing and shortness of breath after playing soccer. On physical examination, she exhibits use of accessory muscles for breathing and diffuse wheezing is heard on auscultation. A peak flow measurement reveals a score of 60% of her personal best, indicating significant airflow obstruction. Chest X-ray shows no acute abnormalities, ruling out other causes of her symptoms.

A 58-year-old male presents with complaints of chest pain and shortness of breath on exertion. Physical exam reveals elevated blood pressure of 160/100 mmHg, a displaced apex beat, and mild bilateral pedal edema. An echocardiogram shows left ventricular hypertrophy and wall motion abnormalities, while lab tests indicate elevated BNP levels.
actual_diagnosis: 25. Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with severe pelvic pain and dysmenorrhea that has worsened over the past year. On physical examination, tenderness is noted in the lower abdominal region, and a bimanual exam reveals nodules in the posterior fornix. Ultrasound shows cystic lesions on the ovaries suggestive of endometriomas. Serum CA-125 levels are elevated, supporting the suspicion of endometriosis.

A 5-year-old male presents with parental concerns about delayed speech and lack of social interactions. Physical examination reveals a lack of eye contact and repetitive hand movements. Developmental assessment indicates significantly delayed language skills, particularly in expressive communication. No abnormalities were found on hearing tests or metabolic screening.
actual_diagnosis: Autism spectrum disorder, ICD-10 code F84.0

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of decreased urine output over the past three days. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and elevated blood pressure. Laboratory results show elevated serum creatinine levels at 3.2 mg/dL and a BUN of 45 mg/dL, indicating acute renal impairment.
actual_diagnosis: Acute kidney injury, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 55-year-old female presents with persistent bilateral joint pain and swelling, particularly in the hands and wrists, lasting for over six weeks. On physical examination, there is notable tenderness and morning stiffness lasting more than an hour. Laboratory tests reveal elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, along with elevated ESR and CRP levels.

A 52-year-old female presents with persistent dryness of the mouth and eyes, reporting difficulty swallowing and a gritty sensation in her eyes. Physical examination reveals bilateral parotid gland enlargement and decreased tear production on Schirmer's test. Laboratory results show positive anti-Ro (SSA) antibodies and elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR).

A 28-year-old woman presents with joint pain and a facial rash that worsens in sunlight. Upon examination, she has a malar rash and tenderness in multiple joints, including the wrists and knees. Laboratory tests reveal positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and elevated anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies. Urinalysis shows mild proteinuria, suggesting possible kidney involvement.

A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of weight gain and fatigue over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a rounded face, thin skin with easy bruising, and abdominal striae. Laboratory tests show elevated cortisol levels and a 24-hour urinary free cortisol level significantly above normal ranges.

A 22-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a 24-hour history of worsening right lower abdominal pain, associated with nausea and loss of appetite. On physical examination, he has tenderness in the right lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and guarding. A CT scan of the abdomen shows an enlarged, fluid-filled appendix with surrounding inflammation, confirming the diagnosis.

A 45-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of vertigo lasting several hours, accompanied by tinnitus and a sensation of fullness in the left ear. On physical examination, she shows unsteadiness during the Romberg test. Audiometry reveals a low-frequency hearing loss in the left ear. MRI of the brain is unremarkable, ruling out other causes of her symptoms.

A 58-year-old male presents to the emergency department with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain that worsens with deep breathing. On examination, he is tachycardic and has decreased breath sounds on the right side. A chest CT angiogram reveals a large pulmonary embolism in the right main pulmonary artery. Arterial blood gas analysis shows hypoxemia with a low PaO2.

A 28-year-old female presents with complaints of intermittent numbness and tingling in her right arm and leg over the past month. On physical examination, she demonstrates a positive Babinski sign and ataxia in her right limb. MRI of the brain reveals multiple demyelinating lesions in the periventricular white matter. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis shows oligoclonal bands, supporting the diagnosis.

A 32-year-old female presents with unintentional weight loss, palpitations, and increased anxiety. On examination, she exhibits a diffusely enlarged thyroid gland, exophthalmos, and brisk deep tendon reflexes. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 10-year-old female presents with complaints of multiple skin lesions and recurrent headaches. Physical examination reveals café-au-lait spots scattered across her torso and axillary freckling. Additionally, a palpable neurofibroma is noted on her left flank. MRI of the brain shows no abnormalities, but the characteristic skin findings are suggestive of neurofibromatosis type 1.

A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe right upper quadrant pain that began suddenly after a fatty meal. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness and guarding in the right upper quadrant, with a positive Murphy's sign. Ultrasound reveals gallbladder wall thickening and pericholecystic fluid, indicative of inflammation. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count and elevated liver enzymes.

A 22-year-old male presents with complaints of recurrent chest pain and palpitations. Physical examination reveals tall stature, long limbs, and arachnodactyly, along with a significant murmur suggestive of aortic regurgitation. An echocardiogram shows dilation of the aortic root and mitral valve prolapse, confirming the suspected diagnosis.

A 65-year-old female presents with chronic knee pain, particularly worsening with activity and improved with rest. On physical examination, there is noticeable joint swelling, crepitus, and reduced range of motion in the right knee. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation, consistent with degenerative changes.

A 58-year-old male presents with fatigue and jaundice. On physical examination, he has notable ascites and spider angiomata. Liver function tests reveal elevated AST and ALT levels, with a low platelet count. An abdominal ultrasound shows hepatic steatosis and signs of portal hypertension.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic liver disease, ICD-10 code K74.60

doctor_vignette: A 68-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and bone pain, particularly in the lower back. On physical examination, there is tenderness over the lumbar spine and decreased range of motion. Laboratory tests reveal a serum protein electrophoresis showing a monoclonal spike in IgG, and a bone marrow biopsy confirms over 30% clonal plasma cells.

A 55-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening abdominal pain and a noticeable bulge in the right groin area for the past week. On physical examination, a palpable, reducible mass is found in the right inguinal region, which increases in size upon coughing. An abdominal ultrasound reveals a hernia sac without any signs of incarceration or strangulation.

A 16-year-old male presents with delayed puberty and concerns about his height. On physical examination, he is noted to be 6 feet tall with gynecomastia and reduced testicular size. Laboratory tests reveal low testosterone levels and elevated luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). A karyotype analysis shows the presence of an extra X chromosome, confirming the diagnosis.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and difficulty breathing for the past week. On physical examination, he has decreased breath sounds on the right side and dullness to percussion. A chest X-ray reveals a right lower lobe opacity consistent with pneumonia. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count and elevated C-reactive protein.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to unspecified organism, ICD-10 code J18.9

doctor_vignette: A 32-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased anxiety over the past month. On examination, she has a fine tremor in her hands, a rapid heart rate of 110 beats per minute, and prominent exophthalmos. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 68-year-old male presents with fatigue and swelling in his legs. On physical examination, he has bilateral lower extremity edema and a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory results reveal a serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL, and a urinalysis shows proteinuria. The patient's history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 75-year-old male presents with increasing shortness of breath and fatigue during exertion over the past few months. On physical examination, a harsh systolic ejection murmur is auscultated at the right second intercostal space, with a diminished carotid pulse. An echocardiogram reveals severe aortic stenosis with a valve area of 0.7 cm² and significant left ventricular hypertrophy.

A 45-year-old male presents with persistent abdominal pain and weight loss over the past six months. On physical examination, he has tenderness in the upper abdomen and signs of malnutrition. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum lipase levels and a CT scan shows calcifications in the pancreas. The patient has a history of heavy alcohol use, which is significant for his condition.

A 72-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that started suddenly. On physical examination, he is found to have an irregularly irregular pulse at 120 beats per minute and mild bilateral lower extremity edema. An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response, and a chest X-ray shows mild cardiomegaly.

A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain, especially during activities such as climbing stairs and prolonged sitting. On physical examination, there is notable crepitus and tenderness over the medial joint line of the right knee, with limited range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 32-year-old female presents with persistent abdominal bloating and diarrhea for the past six months. Physical examination reveals signs of malnutrition, including weight loss and pallor. Serologic tests show elevated tissue transglutaminase (tTG) IgA antibodies and a low hemoglobin level. Endoscopy reveals villous atrophy in the duodenum.

A 28-year-old female presents with fatigue, joint pain, and a butterfly-shaped rash across her cheeks. On physical examination, she has bilateral swelling of the wrists and knees, as well as oral ulcers. Laboratory tests reveal positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels (C3 and C4).
actual_diagnosis: 10. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 24-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations and persistent delusions of persecution. On examination, he appears disheveled, has poor eye contact, and demonstrates disorganized thinking. Routine lab tests are unremarkable, and a brain MRI shows no structural abnormalities.

A 35-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of widespread musculoskeletal pain lasting over six months, accompanied by fatigue and sleep disturbances. Physical examination reveals tenderness in multiple trigger points and a body mass index within the normal range. Laboratory tests show normal complete blood count and metabolic panel, with no signs of inflammation or other underlying conditions.

A 15-year-old male presents with polyuria, excessive thirst, and unexplained weight loss over the past month. On examination, he is found to be dehydrated with a blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg and a heart rate of 110 bpm. Laboratory tests reveal a blood glucose level of 350 mg/dL and ketones in the urine, indicating diabetic ketoacidosis.
actual_diagnosis: 12. Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, she has conjunctival pallor and a heart rate of 100 beats per minute. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 9.5 g/dL and a low serum ferritin of 10 ng/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Iron deficiency anemia, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 62-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unintentional weight loss over the past three months. Physical examination reveals lymphadenopathy in the cervical and axillary regions, along with splenomegaly. A CT scan of the abdomen shows multiple enlarged lymph nodes, and a biopsy confirms the presence of atypical lymphoid cells.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of red, scaly patches on her elbows and knees that have persisted for several months. On physical exam, there are well-defined plaques with silvery scales and some areas of erythema. No significant lab results are noted, but a skin biopsy confirms the diagnosis of psoriasis.

A 32-year-old male presents with severe abdominal pain that started suddenly after a heavy meal. On examination, he has tenderness in the epigastric region and guarding. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows inflammation of the pancreas with no evidence of gallstones.

A 25-year-old female presents with joint hypermobility and recurrent joint dislocations, particularly in her shoulders and knees. On physical exam, she exhibits skin that is velvety and hyper-elastic, along with visible bruising and scarring. A genetic test reveals a mutation in the COL5A1 gene, confirming the diagnosis.

A 58-year-old female presents with recurrent headaches and episodes of dizziness over the past month. On physical examination, she has a palpable splenomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated platelet count of 1,200,000/µL and normal white blood cell and hemoglobin levels. Bone marrow biopsy shows hypercellularity with increased megakaryocytes, consistent with myeloproliferative neoplasm.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent shortness of breath and a chronic cough producing sputum for the past few months. On physical examination, he exhibits wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and a barrel-shaped chest. A chest X-ray reveals hyperinflated lungs, and spirometry shows a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio consistent with obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: 15. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 5-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on her elbows and knees. On physical examination, there are well-defined, erythematous plaques with overlying scale and excoriations. There are no significant laboratory results, as the diagnosis is made clinically based on the characteristic appearance and distribution of the rash.

A 17-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of significant weight loss over the past three months, reporting a current weight of 85 pounds with a height of 5'5". Physical examination reveals bradycardia, lanugo, and a body mass index (BMI) of 14.2. Laboratory tests show electrolyte imbalances, including hypokalemia and hyponatremia, with normal thyroid function tests.

A 65-year-old female presents with gradual vision loss in her peripheral fields over the past few months. On examination, her intraocular pressure is measured at 28 mmHg bilaterally, and a visual field test reveals significant peripheral vision loss. Fundoscopic examination shows cupping of the optic discs, indicating possible glaucomatous changes.

A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation occurring several times a week. Physical examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness but no signs of acute distress. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy shows evidence of esophagitis and the presence of reflux. No additional lab tests are necessary, as the history and endoscopic findings are consistent with GERD.
actual_diagnosis: Acid reflux disease (GERD), ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 30-year-old female presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, she has conjunctival pallor and a heart rate of 100 bpm. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 9.0 g/dL and a mean corpuscular volume of 75 fL, indicating microcytic anemia. Iron studies show low serum ferritin and low serum iron levels.

A 5-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent shortness of breath during play. Physical examination reveals a noticeable cyanosis of the lips and fingertips, a heart murmur, and tachycardia. An echocardiogram shows a ventricular septal defect with right-to-left shunting and pulmonary artery hypoplasia. Chest X-ray indicates cardiomegaly and decreased pulmonary vascular markings.
actual_diagnosis: Rare congenital heart defect, ICD-10 code Q24.9

doctor_vignette: A 58-year-old male presents with jaundice and fatigue. Physical examination reveals ascites, spider angiomata, and palmar erythema. Laboratory tests show elevated liver enzymes (ALT and AST), low platelet count, and a serum albumin level of 2.5 g/dL. Ultrasound of the abdomen reveals a nodular liver consistent with cirrhosis.
