A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation after meals. On physical examination, he exhibits epigastric tenderness but no signs of acute distress. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy shows evidence of mild esophagitis, and a pH monitoring test indicates abnormal acid exposure.

An 82-year-old female presents with increasing forgetfulness and confusion over the past year, often misplacing items and repeating questions. Physical examination reveals disorientation to time and place, as well as difficulty following simple commands. Cognitive testing shows significant impairment in memory and executive function, while CT imaging of the brain indicates generalized atrophy without acute process.

A 10-year-old girl presents with a chief complaint of multiple skin lesions. On physical examination, several café-au-lait spots and neurofibromas are noted on her back and arms. A recent MRI of the brain shows no evidence of tumors, ruling out complications. The family history reveals a maternal uncle with similar findings, raising suspicion for neurofibromatosis type 1.

A 4-year-old male presents with a 5-day history of high fever, conjunctival injection, and a rash. On examination, he has swollen cervical lymph nodes and red, cracked lips. Laboratory results show elevated inflammatory markers, including CRP and ESR, along with a normocytic anemia.

A 52-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of bilateral joint pain and swelling in her hands and feet, which has persisted for the past three months. On physical examination, there is notable morning stiffness lasting over an hour, and tenderness with swelling in the metacarpophalangeal joints. Laboratory tests reveal positive rheumatoid factor and elevated anti-CCP antibodies, alongside an increased ESR.

A 55-year-old male presents to the clinic with complaints of persistent headaches and occasional dizziness. On physical examination, his blood pressure is measured at 160/100 mmHg, and he is noted to have a BMI of 29. Laboratory results show elevated serum creatinine levels of 1.3 mg/dL and a lipid panel indicating hyperlipidemia.

An 82-year-old female presents with progressive memory loss, frequently forgetting recent conversations and misplacing items. On physical examination, she demonstrates disorientation to time and place, along with difficulty in performing simple tasks. A CT scan of the brain shows mild cortical atrophy, particularly in the temporal lobes, consistent with neurodegenerative changes. Laboratory tests reveal no significant abnormalities in routine blood work.

A 7-year-old male presents with recurrent episodes of joint bleeding and prolonged bleeding after minor cuts. Physical examination reveals swollen knees and bruising on the forearms. Laboratory tests show aPTT of 45 seconds (normal range 25-35 seconds) while PT and platelet count are normal. Factor VIII levels are significantly low, confirming the diagnosis.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of joint pain and fatigue lasting for several weeks. On physical examination, she has bilateral swelling of the wrists and knees, a butterfly rash across her cheeks, and oral ulcers. Laboratory tests reveal positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels, indicating an autoimmune process.
actual_diagnosis: 15. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea for the past six months. Physical examination reveals a distended abdomen and signs of malnutrition, including weight loss and dry skin. Laboratory tests show positive tissue transglutaminase antibodies (tTG-IgA) and low hemoglobin levels indicating anemia.

A 72-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. Physical examination reveals bilateral lower extremity edema, jugular venous distension, and a third heart sound (S3). Chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, while BNP levels are elevated at 550 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss, increased heart rate, and anxiety. On physical examination, she exhibits tremors, a warm and moist skin texture, and a noticeable goiter. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, indicating hyperthyroidism.

A 25-year-old female presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and episodes of sudden muscle weakness triggered by laughter. Physical examination reveals no abnormalities, but the patient reports experiencing vivid hallucinations during sleep onset. A polysomnography study shows short sleep latency and REM sleep occurring within 15 minutes of falling asleep, consistent with narcolepsy.

A 22-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations and disorganized speech. On physical examination, he appears unkempt, with flat affect and impaired insight. Neurological assessment reveals no focal deficits, and routine laboratory tests, including CBC and metabolic panel, are within normal limits. A brain MRI shows no structural abnormalities, ruling out other causes of his symptoms.

A 54-year-old male presents with acute pain and swelling in his right big toe, which started suddenly during the night. On examination, the toe is erythematous, warm, and exquisitely tender to touch. Serum uric acid levels are found to be elevated at 9.5 mg/dL, and a joint aspiration reveals needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals under polarized light.

A 25-year-old female presents with persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea for the past three months. On physical examination, she has tenderness in the right lower quadrant and mild abdominal distension. Laboratory tests reveal elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) and a colonoscopy shows skip lesions and cobblestoning in the terminal ileum.

A 45-year-old female presents with fatigue, recurrent infections, and easy bruising over the past month. On physical examination, she has pallor, petechiae on her lower extremities, and splenomegaly. Complete blood count reveals a leukocytosis with 80% immature white blood cells and thrombocytopenia. Bone marrow biopsy confirms the diagnosis of acute leukemia.

A 29-year-old male presents with fatigue and jaundice for the past week. On physical examination, he has scleral icterus and a tender hepatomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes (AST 150 U/L, ALT 180 U/L) and a positive Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg).

A 45-year-old female presents with severe right upper quadrant pain after a fatty meal. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the right upper quadrant and a positive Murphy's sign. Laboratory tests show elevated bilirubin levels and a complete blood count indicating mild leukocytosis. An abdominal ultrasound reveals multiple gallstones in the gallbladder with no signs of cholecystitis.

A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red rash on her hands after using a new dishwashing detergent. Physical examination reveals erythematous, scaly patches with vesicles on the dorsal surfaces of both hands. No systemic symptoms are noted, and patch testing confirms sensitivity to one of the detergent's ingredients.

A 3-year-old female presents with developmental delays and difficulty with motor skills. Physical examination reveals spasticity in the lower extremities, an exaggerated deep tendon reflex, and a scissor gait. MRI of the brain shows periventricular leukomalacia, consistent with a diagnosis of cerebral palsy.

A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath and cough for the past week. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and crackles on auscultation. A chest X-ray shows bilateral infiltrates, and a PCR test for COVID-19 returns positive.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to COVID-19, ICD-10 code J12.82

doctor_vignette: A 63-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and recurrent kidney stones. On physical examination, she has noticeable muscle weakness and abdominal tenderness. Laboratory results reveal elevated serum calcium levels of 12.5 mg/dL and increased parathyroid hormone levels, confirming the diagnosis.

A 68-year-old female presents with progressive rigidity and bradykinesia of the right arm, accompanied by difficulty in speech and occasional episodes of dystonia. On physical examination, there is marked asymmetry, with the right side showing more severe motor impairment and a grasp reflex. MRI of the brain reveals asymmetrical cortical atrophy, particularly in the parietal lobe. Neurological assessment indicates significant cognitive decline with visuospatial deficits.

A 7-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of swelling in the legs and around the eyes for the past week. On physical examination, he has significant bilateral lower extremity edema and periorbital swelling. Laboratory results reveal a 24-hour urine protein of 4.5 grams and serum albumin level of 2.0 g/dL, indicating hypoalbuminemia.

A 55-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent headaches and dizziness for the past month. On physical examination, his blood pressure is measured at 150/95 mmHg, with no other significant findings. Laboratory tests reveal normal renal function and electrolyte levels, ruling out secondary causes of hypertension.

A 67-year-old male presents with complaints of increased urinary frequency, nocturia, and a weak urinary stream. On physical examination, a smooth, enlarged prostate is palpated on digital rectal exam. Urinalysis shows no signs of infection, and a bladder ultrasound reveals post-void residual urine of 150 mL, indicating urinary retention.
actual_diagnosis: Benign prostatic hyperplasia, ICD-10 code N40.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with sudden onset of right-sided facial weakness, unable to smile or close her right eye. On physical examination, there is a notable droop of the right side of her mouth and inability to raise her right eyebrow. Neurological examination shows no other deficits and a CT scan of the head is unremarkable, ruling out other causes.

A 35-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of a dull, bilateral headache that has persisted for the past week. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the scalp and neck muscles, with no neurological deficits noted. Laboratory tests and imaging studies, including a CT scan of the head, are unremarkable.

A 72-year-old female presents with increasing forgetfulness over the past year, often misplacing items and struggling to recall recent conversations. On physical examination, she demonstrates difficulty with short-term memory tasks and her Mini-Mental State Examination score is 22/30. MRI of the brain shows mild cortical atrophy, particularly in the temporal lobes. There are no acute intracranial abnormalities.

A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of numbness and tingling in her right hand, particularly affecting the thumb, index, and middle fingers, which worsens at night. On physical exam, she demonstrates positive Tinel's sign and Phalen's maneuver. Nerve conduction studies reveal delayed median nerve conduction at the wrist, consistent with carpal tunnel syndrome.
actual_diagnosis: Carpal tunnel syndrome, ICD-10 code G56.0

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old male recently returned from a trip to West Africa presents with a chief complaint of high fever and chills. Physical examination reveals splenomegaly and jaundice. Laboratory tests show a positive rapid diagnostic test for Plasmodium falciparum and a hemoglobin level of 9 g/dL indicating anemia.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing difficulty with movement and noticeable tremors in his right hand. Upon physical examination, he exhibits a resting tremor, bradykinesia, and rigidity in the upper extremities. Neurological imaging shows no evidence of structural lesions, but a DaTscan indicates decreased dopamine transporter uptake in the striatum, consistent with Parkinson’s disease.

A 62-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss of 15 pounds over the past two months. Physical examination reveals palpable lymphadenopathy in the cervical and axillary regions. Laboratory tests show elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels and a biopsy of the lymph nodes reveals atypical lymphoid cells. CT imaging confirms multiple enlarged lymph nodes throughout the abdomen and thorax.

A 30-year-old male presents with a persistent cough for the past three weeks, accompanied by night sweats and unintentional weight loss. On physical examination, there are decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right upper lung field. A chest X-ray reveals a right apical cavitary lesion, and sputum analysis shows acid-fast bacilli.
actual_diagnosis: Tuberculosis of the lung, ICD-10 code A15.0

doctor_vignette: A 27-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent intrusive thoughts about contamination and excessive handwashing rituals. Physical examination reveals no significant findings, but the patient reports spending over three hours daily on these compulsions, leading to distress and impairment in her work and social life. No lab tests or imaging are necessary for diagnosis, as symptoms align with obsessive-compulsive disorder criteria.

A 58-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe chest pain radiating to his left arm and shortness of breath. On examination, he is diaphoretic, with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a heart rate of 110 bpm. An ECG reveals ST elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated. These findings are consistent with acute myocardial infarction.

A 3-year-old male presents with a 2-day history of irritability and pulling at his right ear. On physical exam, there is significant erythema and bulging of the right tympanic membrane with purulent discharge noted. No additional imaging is necessary as the clinical findings are consistent with acute otitis media.
actual_diagnosis: Acute otitis media, ICD-10 code H66.90

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with progressive shortness of breath and a persistent cough over the past six months. Physical examination reveals crackles on auscultation and clubbing of the fingers. High-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) of the chest shows ground-glass opacities and reticular patterns consistent with interstitial lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Interstitial lung disease, ICD-10 code J84.10

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old male presents with fatigue, weight loss, and decreased libido over the past six months. Physical examination reveals hypotension and diminished body hair. Laboratory tests show low levels of ACTH, LH, and TSH, along with low cortisol and testosterone levels. MRI of the pituitary gland indicates an empty sella.

A 45-year-old male presents with fatigue and joint pain in his hands. On physical examination, he has a bronze discoloration of the skin and hepatomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum ferritin levels of 800 ng/mL and transferrin saturation of 95%.

A 65-year-old male presents with fatigue and weakness over the past month. On physical examination, he is pale, and there is mild splenomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 10.5 g/dL, elevated serum ferritin, and normal iron studies, consistent with anemia of chronic disease.
actual_diagnosis: Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.9

doctor_vignette: A 67-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening cough and shortness of breath for the past three days. On physical examination, he has decreased breath sounds in the right lower lung field and dullness to percussion. Chest X-ray reveals right lower lobe consolidation, and a sputum culture returns positive for Streptococcus pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Streptococcus pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J18.0

doctor_vignette: A 14-year-old female presents to the emergency department with her mother after experiencing a generalized tonic-clonic seizure at school. On examination, she is currently alert but reports confusion and fatigue following the seizure. A brain MRI shows no structural abnormalities, and her serum electrolyte levels are within normal limits. The patient has a history of similar seizure episodes occurring sporadically over the past six months.

A 35-year-old male presents with a persistent cough lasting three weeks, accompanied by night sweats and weight loss. On physical examination, he has decreased breath sounds in the right lung and dullness to percussion. A chest X-ray reveals an apical cavitary lesion, and sputum analysis shows acid-fast bacilli, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Tuberculosis of the lung, ICD-10 code A15.9

doctor_vignette: A 15-year-old male presents with increasing fatigue and abdominal pain. On physical examination, he has a Kayser-Fleischer ring in his eyes and hepatomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum copper levels and low ceruloplasmin. MRI of the liver shows signs of hepatic cirrhosis.

A 7-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of wheezing and shortness of breath after playing outside. Physical examination reveals bilateral expiratory wheezing and a prolonged expiratory phase. A peak flow measurement shows 60% of his personal best. The patient has a history of asthma-like symptoms exacerbated by environmental allergens, particularly pollen.
actual_diagnosis: Reactive airway disease, ICD-10 code J45.909

doctor_vignette: An 8-year-old male presents with a rapidly growing mass in the left thigh, which has been painful for the past month. Physical examination reveals a firm, non-tender, 5 cm palpable mass with limited range of motion. An MRI of the thigh shows a soft tissue mass extending into the surrounding muscles, consistent with a malignant neoplasm.

A 68-year-old male presents with sudden, severe chest pain radiating to the back. On physical examination, a pulsatile abdominal mass is noted, and the patient exhibits hypotension. A chest X-ray reveals a widened mediastinum, and a subsequent CT scan confirms the presence of a thoracic aortic aneurysm.

A 45-year-old female presents with complaints of aching and swelling in her legs, particularly after prolonged standing. On physical examination, there are prominent, tortuous veins visible on the medial aspect of both lower extremities, with a notable increase in skin pigmentation around the ankles. Venous Doppler ultrasound reveals reflux in the great saphenous vein, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Varicose veins of lower extremities, ICD-10 code I83.90

doctor_vignette: A 54-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a bulge in the right groin that increases in size with standing and decreases when lying down. On physical examination, a soft, reducible mass is palpated in the right inguinal region, with no signs of tenderness or bowel obstruction. An abdominal ultrasound confirms the presence of an inguinal hernia without any complications.

A 45-year-old female presents with extreme fatigue, weight loss, and low blood pressure. Physical examination reveals hyperpigmentation of the skin and orthostatic hypotension. Laboratory tests show hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and an elevated ACTH level with low cortisol levels in the morning.

A 20-year-old male presents with complaints of chest pain and palpitations. On physical examination, he is noted to have tall stature, long limbs, and arachnodactyly. A transthoracic echocardiogram reveals a dilated aortic root. Genetic testing confirms a mutation in the FBN1 gene associated with Marfan syndrome.

A 45-year-old male presents with severe lower back pain radiating down his left leg. On examination, he demonstrates positive straight leg raise and reduced sensation in the left S1 dermatome. MRI of the lumbar spine reveals a herniated disc at the L5-S1 level compressing the left S1 nerve root.

A 45-year-old female presents with severe right upper quadrant pain that started suddenly after a fatty meal. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the right upper quadrant with a positive Murphy's sign. An abdominal ultrasound reveals multiple gallstones within the gallbladder and thickening of the gallbladder wall. Laboratory tests show elevated liver enzymes and bilirubin levels.

A 34-year-old female presents to the emergency department with difficulty breathing and facial swelling after eating shrimp at a restaurant. Physical examination reveals angioedema of the face and lips, wheezing on auscultation, and a rash covering her torso. Laboratory results show elevated serum tryptase levels and a low oxygen saturation of 85%.
actual_diagnosis: Severe allergic reaction, ICD-10 code T78.2

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of facial pain and pressure for the past week. On physical examination, there is tenderness over the maxillary sinuses and purulent nasal discharge is observed. A CT scan of the sinuses shows mucosal thickening and fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses, consistent with sinusitis.

A 35-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of debilitating headaches occurring 15 or more days per month for the past six months, often accompanied by nausea and light sensitivity. Physical examination reveals no neurological deficits, but she exhibits tenderness to palpation in the pericranial muscles. MRI of the brain is unremarkable, ruling out secondary causes of headache.

A 28-year-old woman presents with fatigue, joint pain, and a butterfly rash across her cheeks. On examination, she has mild oral ulcers and swelling in her hands. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and low complement levels (C3 and C4).
actual_diagnosis: 6. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 10-year-old male presents with concerns about social interactions and difficulty understanding nonverbal cues. On examination, he displays limited eye contact, has a narrow range of interests, and engages in repetitive behaviors such as hand-flapping. No significant findings are noted on developmental screening tests, and laboratory tests are within normal limits.

A 54-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, elevated blood pressure at 145/90 mmHg, and a fasting blood glucose level of 180 mg/dL. His HbA1c is measured at 8.5%, indicating poor glycemic control.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 24-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations, stating he hears voices telling him to harm himself. On examination, he exhibits disorganized speech and a flat affect. There are no acute medical issues noted on laboratory tests, and a CT scan of the brain reveals no structural abnormalities. He has a history of declining social and occupational functioning over the past six months.

A 45-year-old male presents with progressive enlargement of his hands and feet over the past five years, along with deepening of his voice and increased sweating. Physical examination reveals pronounced facial changes, including a prominent jaw and enlarged nose, as well as increased spacing between his teeth. Serum growth hormone levels are elevated, and MRI of the sella shows a pituitary adenoma.

A 6-year-old boy presents with recurrent episodes of joint swelling and pain after minor injuries. On physical examination, there is notable hemarthrosis in his right knee and a history of easy bruising. Laboratory tests reveal a prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) and a normal prothrombin time (PT), with factor VIII levels significantly decreased. These findings suggest a bleeding disorder consistent with his symptoms.

A 55-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which began suddenly overnight. On examination, the affected joint is erythematous, warm, and tender to touch. Serum uric acid levels are measured at 9.5 mg/dL, indicating hyperuricemia. Joint aspiration reveals the presence of monosodium urate crystals.

A 28-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of red, scaly patches on his elbows and knees that have been persistent for several months. On physical examination, there are well-defined erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales. There is no evidence of joint swelling or tenderness. Laboratory results show elevated serum levels of inflammatory markers but no signs of infection or other dermatological conditions.

A 32-year-old African American female presents with persistent dry cough and fatigue for the past three months. On examination, she has bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy noted on chest X-ray and mild erythema nodosum on her lower extremities. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) levels and hypercalcemia, raising suspicion for granulomatous disease.

A 45-year-old male presents with confusion and ataxia after a prolonged period of alcohol abuse. On examination, he demonstrates ophthalmoplegia and nystagmus. MRI of the brain reveals lesions in the thalamus and mammillary bodies. Serum thiamine levels are significantly low, confirming deficiency.

A 54-year-old obese male presents with complaints of excessive daytime sleepiness and loud snoring, as reported by his partner. Physical examination reveals a thick neck circumference and signs of hypertension. A home sleep study shows recurrent apneas and hypopneas during sleep, leading to significant oxygen desaturation.
actual_diagnosis: Obstructive sleep apnea, ICD-10 code G47.30

doctor_vignette: A 12-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of wheezing and shortness of breath that worsens at night. On physical examination, he has prolonged expiratory phase and diffuse wheezing bilaterally. Peak expiratory flow rate is measured at 60% of predicted value, indicating significant airway obstruction. A history of allergen exposure and previous asthma attacks is noted.

A 35-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of high fever and severe cough lasting for three days. Physical examination reveals tachypnea, hypoxia with an oxygen saturation of 88%, and bilateral crackles on auscultation. Chest X-ray shows bilateral infiltrates, and a PCR test for SARS-CoV-2 is positive.
actual_diagnosis: Severe acute respiratory syndrome, ICD-10 code B97.21

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male with a history of rheumatic heart disease presents with fever, chills, and a new heart murmur. On examination, he has splinter hemorrhages and petechiae on his extremities. Blood cultures reveal the presence of Streptococcus viridans, and an echocardiogram shows vegetations on the mitral valve.

A 32-year-old female presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss, increased heart rate, and anxiety over the past three months. Physical examination reveals a fine tremor in her hands, and a thyroid exam shows a diffusely enlarged gland. Laboratory results indicate elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of tremors in his right hand that have been progressively worsening over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a resting tremor, bradykinesia, and rigidity in the right upper extremity. Gait analysis shows shuffling steps and decreased arm swing. MRI of the brain shows no significant abnormalities, ruling out other causes of the symptoms.

A 28-year-old female presents to the emergency department with difficulty breathing and swelling of the face and throat after eating shellfish. On exam, she exhibits hives, wheezing, and tachycardia. Vital signs show a blood pressure of 85/50 mmHg, and an oxygen saturation of 88% on room air. Serum tryptase levels are elevated, confirming an anaphylactic reaction.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Severe allergic reaction, ICD-10 code T78.2

doctor_vignette: A 10-year-old male presents with a persistent productive cough and difficulty gaining weight. On examination, he has digital clubbing and coarse lung sounds bilaterally. Sweat chloride test results show elevated levels, confirming the diagnosis. His family history reveals that his older sister was diagnosed with cystic fibrosis at a young age.

A 55-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe pain and swelling in his right big toe that started suddenly overnight. On physical exam, the toe is erythematous, swollen, and extremely tender to touch. Serum uric acid levels are found to be significantly elevated at 9.5 mg/dL, confirming the diagnosis of gout.

A 24-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations and disorganized speech, expressing beliefs that he is being watched. On physical exam, he displays flat affect and poor eye contact. No abnormalities are found on routine laboratory tests, and a brain MRI shows no structural abnormalities. His symptoms have persisted for over six months, impacting his social and occupational functioning.

A 30-year-old female presents with chronic diarrhea and abdominal bloating for the past six months. Physical examination reveals significant weight loss and abdominal tenderness. Serological tests show elevated tissue transglutaminase antibodies (tTG-IgA) and a low hemoglobin level indicating iron deficiency anemia. A duodenal biopsy confirms villous atrophy.

A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a chronic cough that has persisted for several months. On physical examination, he exhibits wheezing, decreased breath sounds, and use of accessory muscles for breathing. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and pulmonary function tests reveal an FEV1/FVC ratio of 60%, consistent with obstructive disease.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with progressive chorea and cognitive decline over the past year. Physical examination reveals involuntary movements, slurred speech, and rigidity. Family history is significant for Huntington's disease, with her mother diagnosed in her early 50s. Genetic testing confirms the CAG repeat expansion in the HTT gene.

A 12-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent wheezing and coughing, especially at night. Physical exam reveals prolonged expiratory phase and use of accessory muscles for breathing. Peak expiratory flow rate is measured at 60% of predicted values, indicating significant airway obstruction. No acute infections are noted on chest X-ray, ruling out pneumonia.

A 68-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent back pain after a recent fall. Physical examination reveals a stooped posture and tenderness over the lumbar spine. A DEXA scan shows a T-score of -3.2, indicating severe osteoporosis. No fractures are noted on X-ray, but the patient's history of frequent falls raises concerns for future complications.

A 10-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of frequent respiratory infections and persistent cough. On physical examination, she has fingertip clubbing and wheezing upon auscultation. Sweat chloride test reveals a high chloride concentration of 90 mmol/L, consistent with cystic fibrosis.

A 26-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea for the past three months. On physical examination, she has tenderness in the right lower quadrant and signs of malnutrition. Laboratory tests reveal elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) and anemia, while a CT scan shows thickening of the terminal ileum consistent with inflammation.

A 58-year-old male presents to the emergency department with chest pain radiating to his left arm, accompanied by shortness of breath and diaphoresis. On examination, he is diaphoretic and has a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg, with a heart rate of 100 bpm and an irregular rhythm. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are elevated at 5.0 ng/mL, indicating myocardial injury.
actual_diagnosis: 7. Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance. On physical examination, she has dry skin, thinning hair, and bradycardia. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated TSH level of 8.5 mIU/L and a low free T4 level of 0.7 ng/dL, indicating hypothyroidism.

A 65-year-old female presents with complaints of gradual peripheral vision loss over the past year. On physical examination, the intraocular pressure is measured at 28 mmHg in both eyes, and a visual field test reveals significant constriction of the visual fields. Fundoscopic examination shows cupping of the optic nerves consistent with glaucoma.

A 62-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of high fever and confusion for the past two days. On physical exam, he is noted to be tachycardic with a heart rate of 120 bpm, hypotensive with a blood pressure of 85/55 mmHg, and has warm, flushed skin. Laboratory results reveal a white blood cell count of 18,000 cells/mm³ and blood cultures are pending, suggesting a possible infectious source.

A 12-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of wheezing and shortness of breath, especially at night and during physical activity. On physical examination, she exhibits prolonged expiratory wheezes and uses accessory muscles for breathing. Peak flow measurements show a marked reduction in her expiratory flow rate, indicating significant airway obstruction.

A 24-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations and delusions of persecution, stating that he believes he is being watched. On examination, he appears disheveled, with flat affect and disorganized speech. Neurological exam is unremarkable, and routine blood tests show no abnormalities. A psychiatric evaluation confirms the presence of psychotic symptoms persisting for over six months.

A 10-year-old male presents with recurrent joint swelling and pain in his knees after minor injuries. On physical examination, there is notable swelling and tenderness in the right knee joint, and he has a history of easy bruising. Laboratory tests reveal a significantly prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) with normal prothrombin time (PT) and low factor VIII levels.

A 24-year-old male presents with chronic lower back pain and stiffness that improves with physical activity but worsens at rest. On physical examination, he exhibits decreased lumbar flexion and tenderness over the sacroiliac joints. MRI of the pelvis reveals bilateral sacroiliitis. He also tests positive for HLA-B27 antigen.

A 55-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe that began suddenly overnight. On examination, the joint is erythematous, warm, and exquisitely tender to touch. Elevated serum uric acid levels of 8.5 mg/dL are noted, and joint aspiration reveals needle-shaped crystals under polarized light.

An 8-year-old boy presents with complaints of difficulty concentrating in school and impulsiveness at home. On examination, he exhibits fidgeting behavior and struggles to stay seated during the visit. No laboratory tests are indicated for diagnosis, but teacher reports confirm persistent inattention and hyperactivity across multiple settings.
actual_diagnosis: 21. Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), ICD-10 code F90.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old male presents for a routine check-up with complaints of fatigue and occasional chest discomfort. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 29, with a notable xanthoma on his elbows. Laboratory results show total cholesterol of 280 mg/dL, LDL of 180 mg/dL, and triglycerides of 200 mg/dL, indicating elevated lipid levels.

A 20-year-old female college student presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, she exhibits conjunctival pallor and tachycardia. Laboratory results reveal a hemoglobin level of 10 g/dL and low ferritin levels of 8 ng/mL, indicating iron deficiency. The patient reports heavy menstrual periods, which may contribute to her condition.
actual_diagnosis: 19. Iron deficiency anemia, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 58-year-old male with a history of diabetes and hypertension presents with fatigue and swelling in his legs. actual_diagnosis: 15. Chronic kidney disease, stage 3, ICD-10 code N18.30

doctor_vignette: A 22-year-old female presents to the emergency department after experiencing a generalized tonic-clonic seizure at home. On examination, she is postictal, exhibiting confusion and muscle soreness, with no focal neurological deficits noted. A CT scan of the head is unremarkable, and routine laboratory tests including electrolytes and toxicology screen return normal. The patient has no previous history of seizures.

A 72-year-old male presents with increasing shortness of breath and fatigue during exertion. Physical examination reveals a systolic ejection murmur best heard at the right second intercostal space, along with a weak pulse and elevated blood pressure. An echocardiogram shows a significantly narrowed aortic valve with a peak gradient of 60 mmHg and a left ventricular hypertrophy pattern on EKG.

A 35-year-old female presents with widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue lasting for over six months. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in multiple trigger points, including the neck, shoulders, and lower back. Laboratory tests show normal complete blood count and metabolic panel, ruling out other conditions. No imaging studies were performed as they would not provide additional diagnostic information.

A 12-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of shortness of breath and wheezing that worsened after playing outside. Physical examination reveals increased respiratory effort with a prolonged expiratory phase and diffuse wheezing on auscultation. Peak flow measurements indicate a significant reduction in airflow, at 60% of her personal best. There are no abnormal findings on chest X-ray, ruling out other acute respiratory conditions.

A 32-year-old female presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss, increased heart rate, and anxiety over the past three months. On examination, she exhibits a fine tremor in her hands, and her thyroid gland is palpably enlarged. Laboratory tests reveal elevated levels of free T4 and suppressed TSH.

A 65-year-old female presents with gradual vision loss and halos around lights. On examination, her intraocular pressure is found to be elevated at 28 mmHg in both eyes, and a visual field test reveals peripheral vision loss. Fundoscopic examination shows cupping of the optic nerve head, indicating possible glaucomatous damage.

A 72-year-old female presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that started suddenly two hours ago. On physical examination, her heart rate is irregularly irregular at 130 beats per minute, and she has mild bilateral pedal edema. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response, and her electrolytes reveal hypokalemia.

A 70-year-old female presents with fatigue and weakness over the past few months. On physical examination, she has pale conjunctiva and mild splenomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 10 g/dL, low serum iron, and elevated ferritin levels, indicating anemia of chronic disease likely related to her history of rheumatoid arthritis.
actual_diagnosis: 16. Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.8

doctor_vignette: A 25-year-old female presents with worsening muscle weakness, particularly in her eyelids and arms, over the past month. On physical examination, she exhibits ptosis and diplopia, with muscle strength significantly improved after rest and worsened with repetitive testing. Serological tests reveal positive acetylcholine receptor antibodies, supporting the diagnosis.

A 35-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, accompanied by nausea and vomiting. On physical examination, he has significant tenderness in the upper abdomen and is noted to have a mild fever. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid consistent with acute pancreatitis.

A 28-year-old female veteran presents with persistent anxiety and flashbacks to combat experiences. On physical examination, she exhibits hypervigilance and a startle response to sudden noises. She reports sleep disturbances and avoidance of situations that remind her of the trauma. No significant abnormalities are found on routine lab tests and imaging.
actual_diagnosis: 20. Post-traumatic stress disorder, ICD-10 code F43.12

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with worsening fatigue and shortness of breath over the past month. Physical examination reveals bilateral lower extremity edema and a blood pressure of 180/100 mmHg. Laboratory tests show serum creatinine of 7.5 mg/dL and a BUN of 60 mg/dL, indicating severe renal dysfunction. Additionally, a urinalysis reveals proteinuria and hematuria.
actual_diagnosis: 18. End-stage renal disease, ICD-10 code N18.6

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old male presents with complaints of progressive enlargement of his hands and feet over the past few years, along with noticeable facial changes including a protruding jaw and enlarged nose. Physical examination reveals increased hand and foot size, thickened skin, and frontal bossing. Serum IGF-1 levels are markedly elevated, and an MRI of the pituitary gland shows a large adenoma.

A 32-year-old female presents with progressive dyspnea and a persistent dry cough over the past six months. On physical examination, she exhibits bilateral crackles on auscultation and clubbing of the fingers. A high-resolution CT scan of the chest reveals ground-glass opacities and reticular patterns consistent with interstitial lung disease. Pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern with a reduced forced vital capacity.
actual_diagnosis: 23. Interstitial lung disease, ICD-10 code J84.10

doctor_vignette: A 52-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of dry mouth and dry eyes for the past six months. On examination, she exhibits bilateral parotid gland enlargement and has a decreased tear production test. Laboratory findings reveal positive anti-Ro (SSA) antibodies and a labial salivary gland biopsy shows focal lymphocytic sialadenitis, consistent with Sjögren's syndrome.

A 28-year-old female presents with persistent feelings of worry and restlessness over the past six months. On physical examination, she exhibits mild tachycardia and tremors of the hands. Routine lab tests, including complete blood count and thyroid function tests, return within normal limits, ruling out physiological causes of her symptoms.

A 12-year-old African American male presents to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain and fatigue. On examination, he demonstrates pallor and jaundice, with splenomegaly noted on palpation. A complete blood count reveals a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL and a peripheral blood smear shows sickle-shaped cells.
actual_diagnosis: Sickle cell anemia, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past three months. On physical examination, he has palpable lymphadenopathy in the cervical and axillary regions as well as splenomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) and a lymphocyte count of 5,000/mm³. A CT scan of the abdomen shows enlarged lymph nodes in the retroperitoneal space.

A 65-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of decreased urine output for the past 48 hours. Physical examination reveals hypertension and peripheral edema. Laboratory tests show elevated serum creatinine levels at 4.5 mg/dL and blood urea nitrogen (BUN) of 35 mg/dL, indicating acute renal impairment.
actual_diagnosis: Acute renal failure, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 3-week-old male infant presents with a chief complaint of failure to pass meconium within the first 48 hours of life. Physical examination reveals abdominal distension and a palpable fecal mass in the lower abdomen. A contrast enema shows a narrow distal colon with proximal dilation, indicating a lack of ganglion cells.

A 23-year-old female presents with left lower abdominal pain that started two days ago, worsening with movement. On physical examination, there is tenderness in the left adnexal area and a palpable mass. An ultrasound reveals a 5 cm simple cyst on the left ovary, with no signs of torsion or rupture.

A 35-year-old female presents with progressive dysphagia for solids and liquids over the past six months, accompanied by episodes of regurgitation and weight loss. On physical examination, she is mildly dehydrated with a distended abdomen. A barium swallow study reveals a dilated esophagus and incomplete lower esophageal sphincter relaxation. Endoscopy shows no obstruction but confirms the absence of peristalsis in the esophagus.

A 62-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath over the past month. On physical examination, he has elevated blood pressure of 160/95 mmHg, bilateral lower extremity edema, and a third heart sound (S3 gallop). A recent echocardiogram reveals left ventricular hypertrophy and reduced ejection fraction of 45%.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain that worsens with activity and improves with rest. On physical examination, there is notable crepitus and tenderness upon palpation of the medial joint line, along with a decreased range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation in the knee, consistent with degenerative changes.

A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a persistent cough for the past six months. On physical exam, he has expiratory wheezes, decreased breath sounds, and a prolonged expiratory phase. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflated lungs, and spirometry reveals a FEV1/FVC ratio of 60%, indicating obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9
